ions = | budget = | staff = <!--Numbers and/or types of staff--> | volunteers = <!--Numbers and/or types of volunteers--> | slogan = | website = {{url |www.city.kyoto.jp/somu/kokusai/lhcs/}} | remarks = | formerly = World Conference of Historical Cities Council | footnotes = }} '''The League of Historical Cities''' (LHC) was established in Kyoto, Japan in 1987.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.uia.org/s/or/en/1100011036 |title = League of Historical Cities |work = Open Yearbook ([[Yearbook of International Organizations]]) |publisher = UIA}}</ref> It holds a biennial world conference and provides cities from different cultures with a platform for bilateral cooperation and mutual learning. The League also acts as a think tank for bilateral cooperation and best practices.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.wien.gv.at/english/politics/international/networks/historical-cities.html |title = League of Historical Cities (LHC) |publisher = Vienna City}}</ref> It aims to strengthen affiliations between historic cities to exchange knowledge and experience and ultimately, world peace by deepening mutual understanding and building on the common foundation of historical cities to strengthen affiliations between cities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ballarat.vic.gov.au/pbs/heritage/league-of-historical-cities.aspx |title=League of Historical Cities |publisher=City of Ballarat |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212061934/http://www.ballarat.vic.gov.au/pbs/heritage/league-of-historical-cities.aspx |archivedate=2013-12-12 |df= }}</ref>
As of March 24, 2014, The League is composed of 102 members from 61 countries and regions of five continents.<ref>{{Citation |url = http://www.city.kyoto.jp/somu/kokusai/lhcs/log-in/pdf/pamphlet/66_all.pdf |title = World Historical Cities |publisher = The League of Historical Cities |issue = 66 |date = March 2014}}</ref> It is in partnership with the [[United Nations Human Settlements Programme]], [[International Council on Monuments and Sites]] and the [[Organization of World Heritage Cities]].
== World Conference of Historical Cities == The league holds a biennial world conference.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.city.kyoto.jp/somu/kokusai/lhcs/publication/pdf/LHC%20Brochure%202013.pdf |title = Brochure of the League of Historical Cities |year = 2013}}</ref> # [[Kyoto]] 1987 "Historical Cities in the 21st Century - Tradition and Creativity -" # [[Florence]] 1988 "Historical Cities in the Future of Mankind" # [[Barcelona]] 1991 "The Memories of and Futures of Cities" # Kyoto 1994 "In Quest of the Wisdom of Historical Cities" # [[Xi'an]] 1996 "Revival of Historical Cities" # [[Kraków]] 1998 "Heritage and Development of Historical Cities" # [[Montpellier]] 2000 "History of Value" # [[Montreal]] 2003 "Conserving and Developing - How? With whom? Why? -"<ref>[http://www.vieux.montreal.qc.ca/2003/index.htm Montréal 2003 - 8th World Conference - League of Historical Cities] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915090303/http://www.vieux.montreal.qc.ca/2003/index.htm |date=2015-09-15 }}</ref> # [[Gyeongju]] 2005 "Today and Tomorrow of the Historical Cities: Preservation and Restoration of the Historical Cities" # [[Ballarat]] 2006 "Sustainable Historical Cities: - Economics, Preservation and Visions for the Future -" # [[Konya]] 2008 "Living Cultural Heritage in Historical Cities" # [[Nara, Nara|Nara]] 2010 "Succession of Historical City with Creative Revitalization" # [[Huế]] 2012 "Defining Universal Heritage Challenges and Solutions"<ref>{{Cite news |url = http://en.nhandan.org.vn/culture/lifestyle/item/1197402-.html |title = World Conference of Historic Cities opens in Hue |date = 2012-04-17 |newspaper = Nhan Dan newspaper}}</ref> # [[Yangzhou]] 2014 "Historical Cities: Ancient Culture Integrated into Modern Civilization" # [[Bad Ischl]] 2016 "Smart, innovative, creative historical cities of the future"<ref>[http://www.eurocities.eu/eurocities/events/15th-World-Conference-of-Historical-Cities-WSPO-A5YKV6 15th World Conference of Historical Cities]. EUROCITIES.</ref>
